SOLID is a set of five design principles that help you write code that’s easier to read, easier to test, and easier to change without breaking everything else. They were originally popularized for object-oriented languages like Java and C#, but they apply just as well to JavaScript — even with its more flexible, less strict nature.
Let’s break down each letter with runnable JavaScript examples;
What Does SOLID Stand For?
S — Single Responsibility Principle
O — Open/Closed Principle
L — Liskov Substitution Principle
I — Interface Segregation Principle
D — Dependency Inversion Principle
Now , let’s discuss about the each principles in detail.
1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
It suggests that a class or module should perform only one role . Simply,a class or module should have a single responsibility or only one reason to change.
❌ The Problem
class Invoice {
constructor(amount) {
this.amount = amount;
}
calculateTotal(taxRate) {
return this.amount + this.amount * taxRate;
}
printInvoice() {
console.log(`Invoice total: $${this.amount}`);
}
saveToDatabase() {
// pretend this saves to a database
console.log("Saving invoice to database...");
}
}This Invoice class does three unrelated things: calculating money, printing, and saving to a database. If you change how invoices are stored, you risk breaking the printing logic too — because it's all crammed into one class.
Now let’s see how can we fix it using Single Responsibility Principle
class Invoice {
constructor(amount) {
this.amount = amount;
}
calculateTotal(taxRate) {
return this.amount + this.amount * taxRate;
}
}
class InvoicePrinter {
print(invoice) {
console.log(`Invoice total: $${invoice.amount}`);
}
}
class InvoiceRepository {
save(invoice) {
console.log("Saving invoice to database...");
}
}2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
Code should be open for extension, but closed for modification.
This means: you should be able to add new functionality without editing existing, working code.
❌ The Problem
function calculateArea(shape) {
if (shape.type === "circle") {
return Math.PI * shape.radius * shape.radius;
} else if (shape.type === "square") {
return shape.side * shape.side;
}
// Every new shape means editing this function again
}Every time you add a new shape, you have to reopen this function and add another if block. That's risky — you could accidentally break circle or square calculations while adding a triangle.
Lets see the solution
class Circle {
constructor(radius) {
this.radius = radius;
}
area() {
return Math.PI * this.radius * this.radius;
}
}
class Square {
constructor(side) {
this.side = side;
}
area() {
return this.side * this.side;
}
}
function calculateArea(shape) {
return shape.area();
}
// ---- Using it ----
const circle = new Circle(5);
const square = new Square(4);
console.log(calculateArea(circle)); // 78.53981633974483
console.log(calculateArea(square)); // 16Now, adding a Triangle class means writing a brand-new class — not touching calculateArea at all. The existing code stays safe and untouched.
class Triangle {
constructor(base, height) {
this.base = base;
this.height = height;
}
area() {
return 0.5 * this.base * this.height;
}
}
const triangle = new Triangle(6, 8);
console.log(calculateArea(triangle)); // 24Notice calculateArea() didn't change at all — it just called shape.area() like before. We only added a new class. That's exactly what "open for extension, closed for modification" means.
3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
An object of a subclass should be able to replace an object of a superclass without breaking the code.
Let’s break down how that works with an example: if L is a subclass of P, then an object of L should replace an object of P without breaking the system. This just means that a subclass should be able to override a superclass method in a way that does not break the system.
❌ The Problem
class Bird {
fly() {
console.log("Flying high!");
}
}
class Penguin extends Bird {
fly() {
throw new Error("Penguins can't fly!");
}
}
function makeBirdFly(bird) {
bird.fly();
}
makeBirdFly(new Penguin()); //crashesPenguin technically extends Bird, but it breaks the expected behavior. Anyone using Bird objects would reasonably assume fly() works — until a Penguin shows up and crashes the app.
The fix is given below;
class Bird {
move() {
console.log("Moving around");
}
}
class FlyingBird extends Bird {
fly() {
console.log("Flying high!");
}
}
class Penguin extends Bird {
swim() {
console.log("Swimming fast!");
}
}
function makeBirdMove(bird) {
bird.move();
}const sparrow = new FlyingBird();
const penguin = new Penguin();
makeBirdMove(sparrow); // Moving around
makeBirdMove(penguin); // Moving around
sparrow.fly(); // Flying high!
penguin.swim(); // Swimming fast!Both sparrow and penguin are Birds, so makeBirdMove() works safely for either one — no crashes, no surprises. That's the Liskov Substitution Principle working correctly: any subclass can stand in for the parent class without breaking the program.
Compare that to before, where calling makeBirdFly(penguin) would've thrown an error — because Penguin was forced to inherit a fly() method it couldn't actually perform.
4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Don’t force objects to implement methods they don’t need.
JavaScript doesn’t have formal interfaces like Java or TypeScript, but the spirit of this rule still applies: keep your objects/classes lean, and don’t bloat them with unrelated methods.
❌ The Problem
class Worker {
work() {}
eat() {}
sleep() {}
}
class RobotWorker extends Worker {
work() {
console.log("Robot working...");
}
eat() {
throw new Error("Robots don't eat!");
}
sleep() {
throw new Error("Robots don't sleep!");
}
}RobotWorker is forced to implement eat() and sleep() even though those methods make no sense for it.
The fix;
class Workable {
work() {}
}
class Eatable {
eat() {}
}
class Sleepable {
sleep() {}
}
class HumanWorker extends Workable {
work() {
console.log("Human working...");
}
}
Object.assign(HumanWorker.prototype, Eatable.prototype, Sleepable.prototype);
class RobotWorker extends Workable {
work() {
console.log("Robot working...");
}
}
const human = new HumanWorker();
human.work(); // Human working...
human.eat(); // Eating food...
human.sleep(); // Sleeping...
const robot = new RobotWorker();
robot.work(); // Robot working...
robot.eat(); // Error: robot.eat is not a functionThat last line is the whole point — RobotWorker was never forced to have eat() or sleep() methods it can't use. It only inherited work(), which is all it actually needs.
Compare that to the earlier bad version, where RobotWorker had eat() and sleep() methods that existed only to throw errors. Here, those methods simply don't exist on RobotWorker at all — which is a cleaner, more honest design.
5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Depend on abstractions, not on concrete implementations.
This principle says that higher-level modules (business logic) should rely on abstraction rather than relying directly on lower-level modules (concretions). It helps us to reduce code dependencies and offers developers the flexibility to modify and expand applications at higher levels without encountering complications.
❌ The Problem
class MySQLDatabase {
save(data) {
console.log("Saving to MySQL:", data);
}
}
class UserService {
constructor() {
this.db = new MySQLDatabase(); // hardcoded dependency
}
saveUser(user) {
this.db.save(user);
}
}If you ever want to switch from MySQL to MongoDB, you have to go inside UserService and change its internals. That's fragile and hard to test.
The Solution
class MySQLDatabase {
save(data) {
console.log("Saving to MySQL:", data);
}
}
class MongoDatabase {
save(data) {
console.log("Saving to MongoDB:", data);
}
}
class UserService {
constructor(database) {
this.db = database; // injected dependency
}
saveUser(user) {
this.db.save(user);
}
}
const service = new UserService(new MongoDatabase());
service.saveUser({ name: "Alice" });
// Output: Saving to MongoDB: { name: 'Alice' }
const service2 = new UserService(new MySQLDatabase());
service.saveUser({name:"Roshan"});
//Output: Saving to MySQL:{name: "Roshan" }Now UserService doesn't care which database it's using — it just calls save(). You can swap databases, or even use a fake one for testing, without touching UserService at all.
Conclusion
The SOLID principle is a fundamental building block for scalable, maintainable, and robust software design. This set of principles helps developers write clean, modular, and adaptable code.
The SOLID principle promotes cohesive functionality, extensibility without modification, object substitution, interface separation, and abstraction over concrete dependencies. Be sure to integrate the SOLID principles into your code to prevent bugs to reap all their benefits.
